priority fires have been established in the following order: belden 88 acres and 0% contained; south 2 026 acres and 46% contained; frey 1 790 and 52% contained; cold 5 512 acres and 62% contained; and scotch 924 acres and 5% contained. the canyon complex is now reporting a total of 42 fires. fires contained-22 (1 396 acres) of which 3 are staffed and the remaining are air patrolled; uncontained-8 (14 087 acres) of which 8 are staffed; utl-12. ciimt3 and plumas forest staffs have a short and long term strategy plan for fires in the canyon complex. the plan includes designation of containment lines based on public and firefighter safety  expected fire progression  resources available  probability of success  values at risk  and suppression costs. additional resources assigned to the canyon complex  especially t1 crews  would lessen the resource and economic loss of the limited suppression strategy currently planned. several crews (t2) and overhead (divs) are reaching there maximum assignment length and will need replacement. the plumas forest area closure for all areas affected by the canyon complex remains in effect.. north ops: on the cold fire  northern  southern and western containment lines were successfully held and improved. on the belden fire  line construction began from the community of belden up the pacific crest trail (indian creek) and chips creek. the fire continues down slope toward the community of belden and precautionary and advisory evacuations are in effect; structure protection is in place. the french fire combined with the bear fire. south ops: lines on the fox fire continued to hold. on the frey fire  fire has crossed the fall river and is threatening the campground of nelsons crossing. the south fire experienced a slopover and continued with dozer and handline construction. on the little fire  line construction is nearing completion on the north perimeter of the fire. on the scotch fire  line construction began on the south side. a contingency plan has been developed for structures on all major fires within the canyon complex due to increased fire activity. resources for this contingency plan are from the butte and canyon complex.. some fires are located in very steep or inaccessible terrain. heavy fuel loading with dry fuel moisture at levels normally not found until late august. national/congressional interest in fuels management pilot project (herger-feinstein quincy library group forest recovery act) for intensive forest management. economic effects to communities dependent on timber industry and tourism. limited communications due to terrain and large incident area. planned music festival in quincy scheduled for july 3-6  2008 at the plumas county fairgrounds. highway 70 is the major transportation route for the area and is currently closed due to fires on the butte complex. lack of sufficient suppression resources  especially t1 or t2 ia hand crews. multiple crews will be reaching their maximum work assignment and will either be demobilized or r/r in the next couple of days. this reduction in resources may affect the predicted containment date and strategies if replacement crews are not assigned.

demobilization is ongoing. as aspen resources become available they are being offered up for re-assignment to other incidents. suppression repair and mop up in north and south repair will continue. fire continues to burn in division m up against sub-alpine rocky ridges and peaks in the kaiser wilderness. a wildland fire module will continue to monitor fire progression and contain fire growth where they can safety engage the fire. fire has been been divided into north repair  south repair  and division m. 0600 209. we will utilize the nws weather data for input into block #30 of the 0600 209 since there will be209's. the ir mapping flight ordered for tonight was utf'd by nicc because the plane was down mechanical. the incident will place another order for an ir flight tomorrow morning for tomorrow pm. 100% containment is not expected until around 8/30/13. there is/inaccessible terrain in division m is also a safety concern to firefighting personnel. the incident has 2 graders  1 masticator  7 excavators  and one front-end loader to assist with rehab operations. reduction in total personnel is a correction to a mistake on 8/14/13 1800 209.. closure on the stumps springs road remains in effect. trail closure continues in the kaiser wilderness with the public being warned of the danger of hiking trails in proximity of the incident.. difficult access and steep terrain  continue to raise safety concerns as crews address suppression repair.

1 010 acres of the fire is on land administered by the six rivers national forest  the remaining acres are in the klamath national forest's direct protection area (dpa).  the ic will continue to work closely with all stakeholders regarding community needs and long range planning for suppression efforts.  the happy camp complex will support initial attack within the klamath national forest.   the klamath national forest is under an emergency closure order in and around the happy camp complex. more information is available at: http://www.fs.usda.gov/klamath/  the acres recorded in block 7 are the cumulative acres for all 18 fires in the happy camp complex.  the following 15 fires are in the happy camp complex and are now declared controlled: kemper (185 acres); delta (150 acres); jackson (29 acres); sutcliffe (27 acres); thompson (17 acres); tims (13 acres); ranch (6 acres); huckleberry (5 acres); bear (4 acres); china (3 acres); mill (2 acres); luther 1 (.4 acres); el capitan (.2 acres); luther 2 (.1 acres); and noranda (.1 acres).  the 441.8 acres for these fires  the 5 225 acre falkstein fire  the 13 110 acre man fire  and all acres of the frying pan fire are included in the complex total recorded in block 7. starting 9/29/14(1)209 will be submitted daily at 1800 hours. fire continued to back toward toms valley creek in division i and flanking up slope into an unnamed drainage east of hooligan lake on division a. fire is burning the understory and staying out of the crowns  moving upslope with more activity than seen since the last rain event. more visible interior smokes were burning today as dryer fuels consumed.
